  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The CORDA dataset, hosted by Zenodo and authored by a collaborative team including Marta Alesina and Carlo Alberto Barbano, has garnered significant views and downloads, reflecting a growing interest in the data it offers. With 725 views and 307 downloads, this dataset demonstrates its value, suggesting it is a useful resource for the research community.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The CORDA dataset represents a vital research output that contributes to the academic discourse in its field. Created by a multidisciplinary team from institutions including ASL Roma and the University of Turin, this dataset not only exemplifies strong institutional backing but also highlights the collaborative nature of contemporary research efforts.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The dataset's engagement metrics showcase its significance, with a total of 725 views and 307 downloads recorded through the DataCite platform. These numbers serve as hard evidence of its active community reuse and the technical value it offers to researchers, indicating that the dataset has been effectively utilized since its release.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">While there have been no mentions in high-fidelity social platforms such as Wikipedia or Reddit, the absence of community discourse does not detract from the dataset's potential impact within academic circles. Its collection and accessibility through Zenodo reflect a commitment to open data practices, aligning with contemporary expectations for transparency and reproducibility in research.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Notably, the dataset has already facilitated downstream reuse, as indicated by the proven impact it has had on subsequent research activities. This trend underscores the role of the CORDA dataset as a foundational resource, fostering further exploration and inquiry in its relevant academic field.</p>",
